# 4. Primary ERM Risks Under Consideration

The primary ERM risk is strategic and operational integration risk: Amazon could acquire an AI last-mile optimization platform but fail to integrate it safely, securely, and effectively into its fulfilment, driver, DSP, customer communication, and data governance systems. This umbrella risk encompasses competitive exposure — entering a logistics software market with established incumbents — as well as cybersecurity and data privacy exposure from a materially new data environment, and strategic ROI risk if the platform fails to deliver expected efficiency gains.

Secondary risks span people (driver and DSP resistance, talent gaps), processes (data quality, change management, regulatory compliance), technology (model drift, API reliability, algorithmic bias), facilities (delivery station readiness, vehicle compatibility), and information security (data breach, unauthorized access, cyber disruption of routing infrastructure).

If left unmanaged, these risks could collectively lead to poor delivery decisions, cybersecurity incidents, regulatory investigations, driver resistance, reputational damage, and reduced ROI outcomes that would undermine both the strategic rationale and financial value of the acquisition.

