# 6. Key Risk Indicators (KRIs)

The table below presents Key Risk Indicators developed across the business's people, processes, technology, facilities, and other critical operational dimensions, reflecting both standard operational risks and the technical and information security risks specific to an AI-powered delivery optimization platform acquisition.

| **Risk Area** | **Sample KRI** | **Warning Threshold** | **ERM Relevance** |
|---|---|---|---|
| People | Driver/DSP adoption rate of AI route recommendations | Below 80% adoption for two consecutive months | Signals poor change management, weak training, or distrust of algorithmic decisions. |
| People | Driver safety incidents per 100,000 deliveries | Increase of 10% or more after rollout | Indicates whether optimization pressure is harming safety or creating reputational risk. |
| Processes | On-time delivery rate | Falls below 95%, or declines by more than 3 percentage points vs. pre-integration baseline, for two consecutive periods | Directly measures whether the acquisition delivers on its core operational rationale. Decline signals integration failure and triggers financial, reputational, and customer trust risk. |
| Processes | Failed delivery / re-attempt rate | Increases above the 30-day pre-integration baseline by 5 percentage points or more for two consecutive months | Sustained re-attempt increases drive cost overruns and indicate AI routing data quality failures. |
| Technology | AI model uptime / availability | Below 99.5% monthly availability | Monitors resilience of the acquired platform as a mission-critical delivery system. |
| Technology | Route recommendation error rate | More than 2% of routes require manual override due to a system error | Detects model drift, bad data inputs, or integration defects. |
| Information Security | High-severity vulnerabilities unresolved beyond SLA | Any critical vulnerability older than 15 days | Tracks exposure of customer address, driver geolocation, and delivery photograph data. |
| Information Security | Unauthorized access or anomalous API activity | Any confirmed unauthorized access event | Protects sensitive routing, customer address, and delivery proof data. |
| Facilities / Assets | Vehicle utilization rate | Falls below target by more than 5% | Shows whether route optimization matches packages, vans, and drivers efficiently. |
| Facilities / Assets | Delivery station late dispatch percentage | More than 5% of routes dispatched late | Links physical facility readiness to AI planning reliability. |
| Compliance / Regulatory | Open regulatory, privacy, or AI governance findings | Any high-risk finding unresolved beyond 30 days; any CCPA or EU AI Act gap without a remediation plan within 14 days | Unresolved findings expose Amazon to enforcement penalties and reputational harm under privacy and AI accountability frameworks. |
| Technology – AI / Algorithm | Delivery outcome disparity by geography or demographic zone | Statistically significant on-time delivery gap (>5%) between highest- and lowest-performing zones, persisting 60+ days post-rollout | Systemic AI-driven disparities create legal liability under consumer protection and civil rights frameworks, including the EU AI Act. |
| Processes – Data Quality | AI model input data quality score | Score falls below 95% in any market for two consecutive weeks; or any critical data feed reports completeness below 90% | Poor data quality is a leading indicator of model drift and route failures, cascading into operational delays and customer-facing delivery failures. |
