# 8. Preliminary Risk Factors and Controls

In preparation for the risk assessment and treatment phase, the table below identifies the contributing factors and preliminary controls for the key risks underlying the proposed acquisition. Technical risk and information security risk are treated as core ERM concerns — not supplementary IT issues — because a failure in the acquired AI platform would simultaneously generate operational disruption, financial loss, regulatory liability, and reputational damage.

| **Underlying Risk** | **Contributing Factors** | **Preliminary Controls / Treatments** |
|---|---|---|
| Strategic Acquisition Risk | High acquisition cost with uncertain ROI; potential overlap with Amazon's existing internal routing tools; heightened antitrust scrutiny given prior deal challenges. | Conduct comprehensive pre-close due diligence covering technology, financial, legal, and antitrust dimensions; define measurable synergy targets with 6-, 12-, and 18-month milestones; establish a Board-level risk appetite statement; engage antitrust counsel at Letter of Intent stage. |
| Operational Disruption Risk | AI routing logic may conflict with physical dispatch realities including parking constraints, building access, package loading sequence, weather, or local delivery restrictions the model has not been trained to handle. | Pilot the platform in three to five selected delivery regions before enterprise rollout; compare AI recommendations against experienced human dispatcher decisions during pilots; require manual override capability at all stations; maintain a documented rollback plan for each market. |
| People and Labor Risk | Driver resistance driven by perceived surveillance and algorithmic pressure; DSP owner concern about loss of dispatch autonomy; insufficient training; AI optimization targets that conflict with safe working conditions or legally required breaks. | Establish driver and DSP feedback loops with documented response commitments; embed safety-first routing constraints as non-negotiable model parameters; develop role-specific training modules; monitor driver safety and adoption KRIs monthly with escalation to VP-level if thresholds are breached. |
| Data Quality Risk | Incomplete or inaccurate address records, traffic feed calibration errors, inconsistent scan timestamps, duplicate customer delivery instructions, or missing exception codes reduce model accuracy and generate unreliable route recommendations. | Implement a data governance framework and quality scorecard covering all primary inputs; deploy master data management protocols for address and customer data; establish automated validation rules that flag inputs below defined quality thresholds before model consumption. |
| Technical Integration Risk | API incompatibility with Amazon's legacy TMS components; latency under peak delivery volume; model drift as demand patterns evolve; scalability constraints during Prime Day and holiday peaks; dependency on third-party map, weather, and traffic data providers. | Conduct a full architecture review and API compatibility assessment as a pre-close condition; perform integration and load testing at simulated peak volume before production deployment; implement continuous model performance monitoring with drift detection alerts; negotiate vendor SLAs for all third-party data dependencies; maintain a fallback routing engine at all stations. |
| AI Model and Algorithm Risk | The algorithm may prioritize speed or cost while underweighting driver safety, weather hazards, parking limitations, accessibility requirements, or legal break obligations; performance degradation or algorithmic bias may emerge in underrepresented geographies. | Establish an AI model governance process with mandatory human review before any production model deployment; conduct pre-deployment algorithmic bias audits by geography, demographic zone, and carrier type; implement an AI explainability logging standard that records key inputs driving each route recommendation. |
